<DOC><DOCNO> AP891120-0152 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-20-89 2324EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     11-20 0217</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0225</SECOND><HEAD>Rebels Claim Soviet Troops Attack Afghan Villages</HEAD><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Afghan rebels said Monday that Soviettanks crossed into Afghanistan's northwestern Faryab province andshelled villages and guerrilla positions near the border.   A statement issued by a coalition of seven rebel groupsheadquartered in Pakistan did not mention any casualties or saywhen the purported attack occurred.   It said a Soviet tank unit shelled areas around Andkhoi, 16miles from the Soviet border.   The rebels frequently claim Soviet warplanes raid northernAfghanistan.   Meanwhile, Afghanistan's official Radio Kabul reportedgovernment soldiers reopened the strategic Salang highway linkingthe capital of Kabul to the Soviet Union.   The broadcast, monitored in Islamabad, said more than 1,000supply vehicles reached Kabul.   Western diplomats have said that for the past several weekssupply convoys were backed up along the Salang highway north ofKabul because of rebel attacks and blockades.   Radio Kabul declared, ``This highway is open forever.''   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979to help the Marxist government battle the anti-communistguerrillas. There were more than 100,000 Soviet military personnelin Afgnaistan for years, but the Kremlin withdrew the last of itscombat forces in February under a U.N.-brokered agreement.   Western diplomats have said more than 300 Soviet militaryadvisers remained in Kabul.</TEXT></DOC>